##One day after the end of life, Chinese people's "video diary" under the epidemic situation

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

For example, in the process of looking at the material and writing the script, Qin Xiaoyu constantly felt the fear and love that people generated under the epidemic. This love, he believes, is the power we have to overcome fear, indifference, selfishness, and hostility.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Screenshot of "one day to live" submitted work. Photo provided by interviewees

By Zhang Huilan, Beijing News

Editor | Wang Jingyi proofread | Zhai Yongjun

This article is about 4491 words and takes about 9 minutes to read

February 9,2020. For most Chinese, the memory of this day is not pretty. The new crown pneumonia epidemic continued to spread, and many saw the National Health Service Call as of Feb. 8,2400, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 37,198.

It's a normal day for an epidemic right now. Many people live in isolation, wear masks and go out with the latest news on their mobile phones... However, this day will be branded in the memory of thousands of people who picked up their mobile phones and cameras for the rest of their lives.

On Feb. 5, Qin Xiaoyu, the documentary director and founder of elephant records, launched an online initiative to invite everyone affected by the outbreak to film footage of their lives at any moment on Feb. 9. After receiving the material, he and his team will work together to produce a documentary, also a Chinese epidemic in the "video diary, " named "a day for the rest of my life. ".

So far, the Qin Xiaoyu team has received more than 3,000 submissions, photographers all over the country and even overseas, are basically Chinese. Qin said that while the team was still sorting through the material and sifting through it with two other editors, he was also working on a script that he hoped would make the film available by the end of March.

Qin Xiaoyu, a 46 year old poet from Inner Mongolia, has been directing or producing documentaries since 2015, focusing on lower class and marginal figures such as poetry loving migrant workers and elderly people at the palliative care. This unique approach to making the rest of my life is based on Qin's long held belief that everyone has a poetic heart, and everyone is creative.

In looking at the material, writing the script process, Qin Xiaoyu constantly confirm this belief, but also constantly feel the outbreak of fear and love. This love, he believes, is the very power we have to overcome fear, indifference, selfishness, and hostility.

Here's a conversation between Qin Xiaoyu and a reporter from the Beijing News:

"For the rest of my life. "

PEELING THE ONION: Why make a documentary like this?

Qin Xiaoyu: this is the first reaction as a documentary filmmaker, because the epidemic itself is of great record significance. It has a great impact from the micro level to the macro level. The macro level is society, and the micro level is personal life, records give the future something to look forward to.

The first is that we are not able to go to the places to film because of the requirements of epidemic prevention and control. The second is that the impact of the epidemic has affected all sectors, all regions and everyone, but obviously no technical team would have the human and material resources to do such a comprehensive record. Third, a single documentary filmmaker would have subjective limitations if more people were involved, each person with their own position and perspective, recorded for their own truth, these things together, can present a more complete truth.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Qin Xiaoyu, creator of one day in my life and director of the documentary film. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Peeling an onion: Why is the title "a day in the life" ?

Qin Xiaoyu: we can understand it in a triple sense. First, it can be understood as "a day in distress. " This epidemic is a disaster for all people and for society as a whole. A lot of things will happen in this disaster, there will be many strong emotions, and there will be special conditions in all aspects, a documentary should be a history of the future.

Second, it can also be understood as an ordinary day in my life. For the vast majority of people, no matter what changes have taken place in society, we still have to live a normal life, even in the midst of disaster, we will do everything we can to make this day as good as possible, there's some fun and happiness.

Besides, it's a day of rebirth. This outbreak will cause many people who are not normally good at or like to think, because of the time and the context of the event, to think about family, the truth, the relationship between people, the relationship between people and animals and so on. This kind of thinking is not only a survey of their own lives, but also includes a kind of social reflection, thus promoting social progress bit by bit. This could be a small piece of the puzzle.

Peeling the onion: was it inspired by the way the film was shot and the title, which is reminiscent of the 2011 release of the American documentary a day in the making? (Note: a day in the life, directed by the British director Kevin Macdonald, is a 95-minute documentary of nearly 4,500 hours of footage taken by Internet users in 190 countries and territories on July 24,2010.)

Qin Xiaoyu: of course, we were also inspired by Fu Sheng Yi Ri. However, the shooting of "floating life" should be around 2010, since the media is not so developed today, people shoot video awareness, level, equipment is not so good.

We're also very different in terms of content. "One day in a floating life" is a kind of daily life landscape, and the life of all the people we filmed, their joys, sorrows, joys, sorrows, and ups and downs, all took place in the big background of the epidemic, which is a kind of daily life in an abnormal state, because that's not how we usually live our lives: we walk around with masks on, or can't get out of the house at all.

As far as creation is concerned, this "abnormal state" will produce a great effect of deviation and defamiliarization, at the same time, it will arouse your emotion. Your various emotions will be aroused in this "abnormal" state. A lot of material from Wuhan, in fact, do not how to shoot, as long as the photographer to their fear, worry, love... This state of the most authentic, especially moving.

Peeling onions: Are there professionals involved, besides the general public?

Qin Xiaoyu: We contacted 30 or 40"fliers" from all over the country, hoping that they could fly a little lower during the day and let us see the expressions of people on the streets. Others play with a Gopro, strap the camera to their bodies for filming, and have also contacted some in-car cameras.

Some of the participants were movie related people I know, like Gioppo, the director of China in the country, who I called around February 5, when he was sick and too scared to go to the hospital, so he took a bunch of pills at home, so I took a picture of myself recuperating at home. Another was Jiang Nengjie, the director of the film the Little Woman, who filmed his grandmother's Day.

I later discovered an interesting phenomenon. These are professional photographers or documentary filmmakers who document more about others or the world around them than non-professionals who mostly focus on themselves. When you need a plot point, a particularly touching speech, often these non-professionals can bring you more surprises.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"polyphonic, noisy. "

Peeling the onion: What are the main elements and emotions in these shots?

Qin Xiaoyu: what accounts for a large proportion is to film myself in isolation at home. Some took pictures of their surroundings, such as going to the pharmacy, the supermarket, and walking around the neighborhood. Documentary workers, aerial "fliers" , photographers and other professionals will record the public space of some things, such as road blocks, inspection. And then there are those that are closely related to the epidemic, like the patients in the shelter hospital, the paramedics, the delivery guys, the volunteers, who are in a working state, recording their work.

What I have seen so far is that there are emotions, emotions, emotions, sadness, fear, and even those without any obvious emotions. We would have liked it to be polyphonic and noisy, rather than a work of unity.

Peeling an onion: tell me something from Wuhan.

Qin Xiaoyu: Wuhan has a lot of moving material. A young man went up to the roof of their house and pointed to a place where the lights were dim. He said that it was Lingjiao Lake. The Hubei Provincial Integrated Hospital of traditional Chinese and Western medicine near the lake was the first place to admit patients with new crown pneumonia, the South China seafood market is just a kilometer away. He also spoke of his feelings, saying that during the period of the siege, when people's activities had decreased, he apparently heard more bird calls and PM2.5 levels had dropped. It was the 16th day of the 1st Lunar Month. He held his mobile phone to introduce his position. The camera turned to the moon.

A girl in Wuhan, she first let the camera to their own, said "recently Wuhan... " on the go. "never mind, let's take a look at Wuhan at 2:00 in the morning, " she said, her voice trembling as she held the phone out of the window. The picture was dark, "You see there aren't many lights out there, it's more obvious during the day, it's like the whole city is on pause. "

There's also a doctor who goes by the online name "two-egg King. ". He traveled from Ningxia to Hubei Province to support the team. The filming took place in a hospital. Facing the camera, he spoke of his fear that the epidemic would not end soon, and that he would catch the disease or even die from it. Although the background is a little overexposed and the composition is not good, but because they are closest to the danger, it makes the fear more real and has a strong resonance.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Peeling onions: What else impresses you?

Qin Xiaoyu: There is a girl in Ningbo, the Spring Festival can not go home, her grandmother is a rat, just birthday, she made three small mice with dough, write "96(year) happy. ".

Another girl, who had been in contact with a confirmed patient and whose information had been exposed in a neighborhood group, immediately received a crank call. She said she felt the world's deep hatred for her. She said she was not afraid to die, but she was afraid to die in discrimination.

There was a girl in Shantou who said her best wishes to the riverside scenery, including her ex-boyfriend. I wonder if this outbreak has given her a new perspective on the two men's story. She says the impact of the epidemic is to treat each day as if it were your last, so that each day will be cherished.

One family filmed them making masks in the house, while a father and son played football. Another example is a lame duck walking on a field and a broadcast in Sichuan dialect floating in the air: "everyone has done a good job on this. Every day is the Spring Festival. If it is not done well, this is the last Spring Festival. " Such material is particularly abundant, full of imagination.

Love is the power to overcome fear, indifference, selfishness, and hostility

Peeling the onion: What to do after you've gathered the material?

Qin Xiaoyu: collate material, make notes. We have 8-10 people working on the material. I've seen sixty per cent of the material so far. Then the rough cuts, then the fine cuts. I thought editing and production was going to be a huge problem, but as I looked at the material and made the editing script, my confidence grew. Confidence comes mainly from the richness of the material and the degree of surprise.

I have always had the understanding that everyone has a poetic heart and everyone has creativity. On the one hand, this epidemic has aroused people's feelings of dilemma, fear, confinement and so on, but on the other hand, because everyone is so "pent up" that they can not go out, it's an expression that releases the tension.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The documentary team is stepping up production

Shucking onions: will these materials help raise awareness of the epidemic?

Qin Xiaoyu: After the outbreak, most of what you can see is happening in public spaces, such as government departments meeting to study, construction sites under strain, hospitals treating patients, and empty streets. But most of the material we received was closed off, and the photographer returned to his private space. We only knew how we lived at home. We didn't know what the difference was between families in the countryside and those in the cities. What was the difference between the epidemic areas and the epidemic areas, what was the difference between middle-class families and those working at the bottom, what are the interesting things and conversations that take place in these fields?

For example, a police officer on duty appeared in the submission. He photographed himself at work and at home. You can see that after he got home, he would hang the shiny police uniform in the yard and sterilize it. He would not take it into the house. Normally, all the footage we see in public records is of the police working on the streets, how he checks up and how he takes his temperature, but in fact he has his emotions, his hobbies, his family, in these materials, he suddenly became a sweet, loving person, not just a professional identity.

Peeling the onion: what meaning do you want to convey when the film is finished?

Qin Xiaoyu: The mission of the documentary is to record the truth, especially in the present complicated situation, it is especially important for everyone to present the truth in his own eyes based on his own observation and position, to help us understand the truth, to record the life history of every ordinary person.

In addition, this form of national record can itself give us a revelation that everyone's life experience is worthy of respect, is valuable, there is no hierarchy.

Moreover, the fear and love that people engender under epidemic situation, also will be an important theme of the film. This fear, both for themselves and their families and friends infected with the disease, but also for the continuing impact of the epidemic anxiety, and even spread to the people of Hubei for no reason discrimination, you will feel people's relationships are suddenly pulled apart, and even break apart, we've created a plague that's not just a plague. But on the other hand, we also see in the material, retreat into the family, many people will rethink the meaning of the family, re-feel their previously unaware of the good. This love is the power we have to overcome our fears, our indifference, our selfishness, our hostility.
